library(ggplot2)

  • Guiding Question - What are the factors that make a youtube channel successful.

  • I found these data sources from an website called Kaggle.

  • The dataset YouTube Top 4000 Channels based on subscribers was collected and is being maintained by Libin Mathew. The data YouTube Trending Video Statistics with Subscriber Data is was collected and is being maintained by an unknown coder that identifies himself on Kaggle as Mr.SG.

  • YouTube Top 4000 Channels based on subscribers was created a year ago 2019-04-18. YouTube Trending Video Statistics with Subscriber Data was created 2018-03-24. Both of these datasets purposes were not presented but they both seem to serve the purpose of giving indepth information about Youtube.

  • Each case in YouTube Top 4000 Channels based on subscribers represent the top channels based on subscriber number and also number of views. There are over a thousand cases in this dataset. Each case in YouTube Trending Video Statistics with Subscriber Data represents the trending youtube videos with respect to subscribers. There is also over a thousand cases in this dataset as well.

  • Some variables that I plan on using are the #subscribers, name, #followers, #videos, #views, and #likes. My primary datasource is Youtube.csv. And my secondary is USvideos_modified.

  summarise(count = n())

USvideos_modified %>%
  head(20)

Join operation to better understand the youtuber

YouTube %>% 
  select(userID, `userID-href`)

A tidy form of the data to show that userId is directly correlated to name. It also give a sense of what uploads users are making

Youtuber <- 
  YouTube %>%
  select(userID, `userID-href`) %>% 
  left_join(YouTube %>% select(name, uploads),
            by = c("userID" = "name")) 
print(Youtuber)

The maximum and mininum number of views per channel are shown in the figure below.

YouTube %>%
  summarise(averViews  = mean(videoviews, na.rm=TRUE),
            greatestViews = max(videoviews, na.rm = TRUE),
            leastViews = min(videoviews, na.rm=TRUE))
YouTube %>%
  group_by(channeltype) %>%
  summarise(avg = mean(uploads, na.rm = TRUE), 
            greatestViews = max(videoviews, na.rm = TRUE),
            MostSubs = max(subscribers, na.rm = TRUE),
            money = max(YearlyEarnings, na.rm = TRUE)
            )

From the figure above it can be inferred that the higher the views and subscribers the higher the channels revenue.

Based on these datasets it can be infered that Entertainment youtubers are popular and have a stronger presence then any other category on Youtube.
